  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and agreements designed to combat money laundering, including:\n\n1. Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations\n- Global standard-setting body for anti-money laundering efforts\n- Provides guidelines for countries to implement\n\n2. United Nations Conventions\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- UN Convention Against Corruption\n\n3. International Monetary Fund (IMF) Guidelines\n- Provides frameworks for preventing financial crimes\n\n4. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision Standards\n- Sets international banking regulations\n\n5. European Union Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Establishes rules for EU member states\n\n6. Bank Secrecy Act (US)\n- Requires financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n\nMost countries have domestic laws implementing these international standards, requiring banks and financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report large or suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement compliance programs\n\nThese laws aim to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income.",
